  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I just bought an Activa 110 cc bike and technicians have advised me against riding it above 40 kmph until the first 750 km. Why is that so?",
  "response": "Congratulations on your new Activa 110 cc bike! The advice given by the technicians is likely related to the break-in period for your new bike. During the first few hundred kilometers, it's important to allow the engine and various components to settle in properly. Here are some reasons why they might advise you to keep the speed below 40 kmph until you've reached 750 km:\n\n1. **Engine Break-In:** The engine is new, and its internal components need time to wear and seat correctly. Driving at moderate speeds helps ensure that these components settle in smoothly without causing undue stress or damage.\n\n2. **Avoiding Excessive Heat:** New engines can generate additional heat, especially if driven at higher speeds. Keeping the speed lower helps prevent overheating and ensures the engine can cool adequately.\n\n3. **Component Wear:** Apart from the engine, other parts like the transmission, brakes, tires, and suspension also need time to break in. Gradual use at lower speeds can help prolong their lifespan and ensure optimal performance.\n\n4. **Lubrication:** Proper lubrication is critical for all moving parts, and during the break-in period, the lubrication process ensures that oil reaches and coats every part adequately. Higher speeds can sometimes disrupt this process in a new engine.\n\nBy following the break-in advice and riding conservatively during the initial period, you can help ensure the longevity and reliability of your bike. After the first 750 km, you can gradually start to increase your speed and enjoy your Activa to the fullest.",
